VI. The serm of a People is taken away, when the participation in common rights no longer subsists, either at all, or at least, pcrfectly: whether individuals are reduced into a state of pcrsonal slavery, as the Myceneans sold by the Argives, the Olynthians by Philip, the Thebans by Alexander, the Bruttians sentenced to slavery at public works by the Romans ; or retaining their liberty* are deprived of their political power. Thus Livy relates of Capua, that the Romans deter- mined that it should be inhabitcd as a hamlet merely, with no muni- cipal body, no senate, no assembly of the people, no magistrates3 a collection of individuals without authority, among whom a judge sent from Rome should administer justice, and accordingly Cicero says, that there was no image ofa State left at Capua. The same is to be said of peoples reduced into the form of a province, and of those who are brought under the authority of another pcoplc. Thus Byzantium was put under Perinthus hy Severus, and Antiochia under Laodicea by Theodosius.
